Variable Descriptions¶

battery_power: Total energy a battery can store in one time measured in mAh.

blue: Has bluetooth or not.

clock_speed: Speed at which microprocessor executes instructions

dual_sim: Has dual sim support or not

fc: Front camera megapixels

four_g: Has 4G or not

int_memory: nternal memory in Gigabytes

m_dep: Mobile depth in cm

mobile_wt: Weight of mobile phone

n_cores: Number of cores of processor

pc: Primary camera megapixels

px_height: Pixel Resolution Height

px_width: Pixel Resolution Width

ram: Random Access Memory in Megabytes

sc_h: Screen Height of mobile in cm

sc_w: Screen Width of mobile in cm

talk_time: Longest time that a single battery charge will last when talking on phone, in hours

three_g: Has 3G or not

touch_screen: Has touch screen or not

wifi: Has wifi or not

price_range: This is the target variable with value of 0(low cost), 1(medium cost), 2(high cost), and 3(very high cost)

General Characteristics¶

Look at the characteristics of each of the variables.¶

Numeric variables: count, mean, standard deviation, minimum, quartiles, and the maximum.¶

The data set conveniently has all numerical data types. There are some boolean variables(blue, wifi, touch_screen, etc.) that are represented by 0's and 1's in the original data set. The other variables are continuous(int_memory, mobile_wt, etc.) or discrete (n_cores, pc, etc.).

Battery Power seems to be relatively uniform ranging from 500 millamps per hour to 2000 milliamps per hour. It would be interesting to see this compared to features in the phone. The number of features in the phone could indicate more usage of battery power (including in the background) as well as further advancement in technology in the phone and therefore greater battery technology in the phone.

In order to group battery power we will bin the variable into 3 groupds. Low being the lowest battery power and high being the highest.

<AxesSubplot:>

Phone depth, width, screen height, and screen width may be interesting to compare and try to derive a timeframe from. The size of phones, which impacts each of the 4 previous mentioned variables, has fluctuated over the years. Phones started out large in order to hold eachnology. As time went on and phone parts became smaller, so did the phones and this showed that you had a new phone with the latest technology so the smaller the phone, the better. Then, times switched due to the amount of technology actually in the phone. People began carrying around little computer in their hand and therefore the desire to have a decent sized screen grew. With streaming capabilities and the different tasks a person could get done, phones almost grew to the size of mini tablets. Now, it seems that the trend is going back down and the desire to have a large phone is beginning to subside.

It is evident from the cross tabulation bar graph that when phones are cheaper, they have lower battery power and when they are more expensive, they have higher battery power. Battery power is essential and a very important consideration when purchasing a phone. If buying a use phone, even if the phone is very advanced if the battery doesnt last very long, you won't really be able to use the features of the phone anyways so it brings the price of the phone way down. In the two middle rice ranges of groups 1 and 2, there may be a mix of this occuring. Battery life may be moderate but the technology is good or bad or the battery life is really good or really bad but the phone the techology is opposite.

A general observation is the high correlation between the target variable, price_range, and the ram variable. This was expected during exploratory analysis but theis correlation table confirms it.

There may be a way we can create a feature that captures both of those features.
